WEBVTT

00:00:00.760 --> 00:00:02.360
Hi, I'm Ava Hoffman.

00:00:02.360 --> 00:00:05.720
I'm here today to tell you about Ten Simple Rules for Teaching Intro to R.

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:10.040
There's no shortage of amazing content out there.

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:12.960
Some of the creators are maybe here in this room with us right now.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:16.360
But a lot of this material is directed at learners

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:19.920
who are really self-motivated and can work through content independently.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:25.240
We know there's value in synchronous education,

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:29.040
whether that's in a classroom or on an online platform like Zoom.

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:31.520
Some people just need a little bit more hands-on help

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:33.439
when it comes to learning R programming.

00:00:35.439 --> 00:00:37.959
But then the question becomes, who's going to teach it?

00:00:37.959 --> 00:00:40.560
And that might end up being you,

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:42.200
whether that's in a traditional classroom

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:44.200
or maybe you're doing a workshop for your colleagues.

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:47.240
But a lot of people feel unprepared to do this.

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:52.360
And so I'm here today to hopefully alleviate a little bit of the stress

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:56.480
when it comes to being a new instructor teaching new R users for the first time.

00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:00.279
My colleague, Carrie Wright, and I have taught an introduction to R

00:01:00.279 --> 00:01:02.799
to hundreds of public health professionals,

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:05.879
graduate students and undergraduate interns,

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:09.199
all of whom are going to lack the computer science background

00:01:09.199 --> 00:01:11.480
and maybe are a little uncomfortable from the start.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.239
And we've distilled our top 10 takeaways

00:01:16.519 --> 00:01:18.760
so you can get up and running teaching R quickly.

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:21.919
It's kind of like a listicle.

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:23.360
All right.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:24.440
All right.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:26.720
And with the few minutes I have left,

00:01:27.199 --> 00:01:29.800
I'm going to go through a couple of nuggets of information,

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:31.919
hopefully, to prepare you a little bit.

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:34.360
So first, we want to set ourselves up for success.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:39.080
We like to make it an intensive, minimize those distractions,

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:41.040
turn off the Slack notifications.

00:01:41.199 --> 00:01:43.040
It's good for you and for your students.

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:45.720
Teach as a team.

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:48.879
It's great to have a support network with you and your colleague.

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:51.480
You could support each other and grow in your teaching journey.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:54.559
And I want to linger on this rule a little bit,

00:01:54.559 --> 00:01:57.680
and that is to teach reproducibly using dynamic documents

00:01:57.680 --> 00:01:59.480
like R Markdown and Quarto.

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:02.400
Not only is it going to teach, help your learners

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:04.440
learn reproducible practices,

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:09.160
but keep the pace with rapid updates in our ecosystem.

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:11.639
And not only that, but platforms like GitHub

00:02:11.639 --> 00:02:14.479
have great project management features like projects and issues.

00:02:14.479 --> 00:02:17.800
I know I forget pieces of things I want to change immediately

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:20.119
and making issues helps me keep track of that.

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:23.080
Keep it practical.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.520
I tell my students a lot to prioritize intuition over memorization.

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:30.919
The reality is you're going to be able to Google things

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:32.240
and look at the documentation.

00:02:34.559 --> 00:02:36.880
Make sure you focus on live code and lab time.

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:39.600
Get your hands in the code right away and start making mistakes.

00:02:42.039 --> 00:02:43.279
Start with data wrangling.

00:02:43.279 --> 00:02:46.679
Most of our learners statistically who start learning R

00:02:46.679 --> 00:02:48.080
are not going to be computer scientists,

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:51.839
so not a thing we want to bog down in the beginning.

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:55.199
And then again, I want to linger on this one,

00:02:55.199 --> 00:02:58.880
so end the course or perhaps a workshop with a project.

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:04.919
Research shows that applying what you've learned in real life context

00:03:05.119 --> 00:03:09.399
is going to foster better comprehension, more curiosity

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:12.839
and more motivation for the rest of your R learning journey.

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:16.960
We've had students cover everything from Pokemon data

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:20.360
to art installations and really meaningful public health projects.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:25.160
And finally, know your learners.

00:03:28.039 --> 00:03:31.479
So we suggest committing to either Tidyverse or Base R.

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:34.160
Learners tend to get a little confused if you mix them up,

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.759
and we find Tidyverse works really well for our public health audience.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:41.839
Know the common pitfalls.

00:03:41.839 --> 00:03:44.559
You're likely to encounter mistakes over and over again,

00:03:44.559 --> 00:03:47.080
such as, you know, loading particular packages.

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:49.080
Students often get caught up on that.

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:52.160
And so knowing ahead of time can help you be prepared.

00:03:54.399 --> 00:03:57.080
And then the last piece and probably most important

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:01.479
bit of advice I can give is to give and get feedback often.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:05.000
Your teaching or your content is never going to be perfect

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.639
the first time around. You can always make it better.

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:11.960
So we typically will survey our learners

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:15.880
throughout the course anonymously and try to get a little bit

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:17.640
more information on what we can do better,

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:20.600
what we might modify and how we can better meet their needs.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:24.079
And I just want to leave you with this.

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:25.359
This is a link to our paper,

00:04:25.359 --> 00:04:28.959
if you want to read more about the ten simple rules or check out the slides.

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:31.640
But if you're new to teaching, good luck.

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:32.320
You're going to do great.

